<HL> NutraSweet Says Sweetener Cleared For Expanded Use </HL>
<AUTHOR> Carlee R. Scott (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> PFE CDGB MTC </CO>
<IN> FOD BVG </IN>
<G> FDA </G>
<DATELINE> DEERFIELD, Ill.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NutraSweet Co. said the Food and Drug Administration has approved the use of its low-calorie sweetener, aspartame, in six more food-product areas. 

   The government approved the sweetener for use in yogurt-type products; flavored milk; aseptic beverages; ready-to-serve gelatin desserts; wine coolers, and dairy and non-dairy frozen desserts. 

   NutraSweet wouldn't estimate the amount of sales that the new product areas will generate for the company. 
Those products generated more than $6 billion in total U.S. sales last year, including frozen desserts with $3 billion and yogurt products with $1.15 billion, according to NutraSweet. 

   In 1987, NutraSweet, a Monsanto Co. unit, had sales of $722 million, compared with $711 million in 1986. 

   The company said it has been working with several of its customers, including Beatrice Co., Pfizer Inc., Canandaigua Wine Co. and Squirt &amp; Co., to develop products in these areas that will contain NutraSweet. 
Some of these products are expected to be in supermarkets in the near future, NutraSweet said. 

   Nearly 1,250 products world-wide contain NutraSweet's aspartame, and getting approval for as many products as possible is important for the company. 
Currently it is the world's largest and only U.S. producer of aspartame. 
Its U.S. patent expires in 1992. 

   Aspartame, which is marketed under the NutraSweet brand name, currently is used in powdered soft drinks and tea, milk-based drinks, toppings and desserts, and over-the-counter medications. 
In November 1986, the FDA approved the use of the sweetener in juice drinks, frozen desserts on a stick, tea beverages and breath mints. 

   NutraSweet said it has also requested FDA approval for use of aspartame in such products as hard candy and cough drops, syrups and topping, and baked goods and mixes. 

</TEXT>
