<HL> Monsanto's NutraSweet Co.
Loses Aspartame Monopoly</HL>
<DD> 07/08/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> MTC CANDA
FOOD &amp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB) </IN>
<DATELINE> ST. LOUIS  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NutraSweet Co.'s six-year monopoly on the sale of aspartame in Canada ends today, after the Monsanto Co. unit lost its exclusive right to sell the non-sugar sweetener last week despite an attempt to get Parliament to extend the patent for five years. 

   The effort was blocked by a coalition of consumer groups and trade organizations, as well as by potential competitors that hope to get a piece of a business with estimated annual sales of 300 metric tons, or almost $30 million. 

   NutraSweet said it requested the extension because it hadn't been able to benefit from the full length of its patent. 
Though it received the patent in 1970, regulatory delays blocked sale of aspartame in Canada until 1981. 

   The change promises to open the door to a host of importers and manufacturers that hope to tap the Canadian market for aspartame, the only non-sugar sweetener permitted by the Health Protection Branch, a regulatory agency. 
Already, Toronto-based Semmons-Taylor Inc. has promised to begin importing Japanese aspartame by the end of this week. 
Synthetech Inc., a tiny Boulder, Colo., biotechnology concern, hopes to license an aspartame-making process in Canada. 
Soft-drink makers account for 90% of the Canadian aspartame business. 

   NutraSweet doesn't expect the change in Canada to affect its U.S. operations, which make up the bulk of its $711 million in annual aspartame sales. 
The company in 1983 received from Congress an extension of its U.S. patent, which expires in 1992, and still holds patents on its manufacturing process. 

</TEXT>
