<HL> Aspartame Study
Says It Can Help
Obese People Diet
---
Harvard Researchers Found
Group Lost More
By Using the Sweetener
---
By David Stipp
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 10/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> FOOD &amp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB) </IN>
<DATELINE> BOSTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The artificial sweetener aspartame, known commercially as NutraSweet, helps at least some obese people stick to diets and shed pounds, according to a study by Harvard Medical School researchers. 

   The study contradicts results of previous aspartame research, but it isn't likely to end medical controversy about NutraSweet's value as a dieting aid. 
The controversy heated up last year when two British researchers at Leeds University reported a study in the medical journal Lancet indicating that ingesting aspartame can sometimes stimulate appetite and make successful dieting harder. 
The British study, in which 95 people took part, involved controlled consumption of aspartame doses over several hours. 

   By contrast, the recent Harvard study, funded by Monsanto Co.'s NutraSweet unit, was the first to investigate aspartame's use in real-life diet situations. 
Conducted with 59 obese people in a 12-week weight-reduction program, it showed that women who consumed aspartame-containing foods, such as puddings and diet drinks, lost an average 16.5 pounds. 
That was about four more pounds than the average weight loss for women in the study whose diets didn't include sugar substitutes but contained the same number of calories. 
The aspartame group also reported having more energy and other indications of well-being compared with the other group. 

   The study showed, however, almost opposite weight-loss results for male participants, but the researchers emphasized that not enough men took part to yield statistically significant results. 

   "The aspartame allowed people to achieve mouth pleasure without adding calories, and that improved compliance with their diets," said George Blackburn, who led the study. 
"We think the protocol of the aspartame study is representative of a new generation of diets" in which "you don't have to suffer or be in pain to solve the disease of obesity." 
He added that both groups of dieters participating in its study consumed high-fiber, low-fat foods and took part in an exercise and behavior-modification program. 

   The Harvard researchers said their study was a preliminary investigation that will followed be by a longer one with more definitive results. 
Dr. Blackburn also said that the study doesn't indicate aspartame's value for dieters of normal weight. 

   Nutritionists hailed the Harvard study as a significant finding, but they cautioned that further research will be needed to resolve questions about NutraSweet and dieting. 
The Harvard study "is certainly significant, but it isn't the last word," said Judith Wurtman, a researcher who has studied aspartame at Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
"Many people tend to crave carbohydrates and gain weight in the winter. 
One wonders whether an aspartame diet would have had the same results with those people when they crave carbohydrates the most." 

</TEXT>
