<LP>
   The company that made NutraSweet a household name is
developing a new substance it already is heralding as the
sugar replacement of the 21st century.
   Called Sweetener 2000, the ingredient has 10,000 times the
sweetness of sugar, making it perhaps the world's sweetest
chemical -- and literally zero calories.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But don't look to reach for it in your sugar bowl anytime
soon. NutraSweet Co. isn't expected to seek Food and Drug
Administration approval for its ingredient before 1994.
Nonetheless, the Monsanto Co. unit believes that Sweetener
2000 offers a far broader opportunity than NutraSweet, which
is the world's most popular artificial sweetener.
   "It's targeted to replace sugar," said Michael L. Losee,
who heads NutraSweet's research-and-development department.
Says Robert E. Flynn, NutraSweet's chief executive officer:
"I jokingly tell Monsanto's board that if we do this, maybe
we could buy Monsanto."
   But NutraSweet could encounter stiff competition with its
new miracle ingredient. Already seeking Food and Drug
Administration approval are Johnson &amp; Johnson's sucralose,
which is 600 times sweeter than sugar, and Pfizer Inc.'s
alitame, which is 2,000 times sweeter. Coca-Cola Co. also
recently patented a class of sweeteners as much as 1,900
times sweeter than sugar, although it says it isn't currently
contemplating any commercial applications.
   The new sweetener can be used in baking and has an
indefinite shelf life. NutraSweet says its product also costs
less than one cent a pound to produce -- compared with many
times that for sugar.
   "We have changed the cost structure of sweeteners with
this," Mr. Losee says.
   By contrast, NutraSweet is only 200 times sweeter than
sugar; it breaks down at high temperatures and is far more
expensive than sugar. Although the company won't say what it
charges for NutraSweet, some analysts believe the sweetener
costs customers upwards of $50 a pound.
   NutraSweet officials wouldn't say if Sweetener 2000 will
eventually make NutraSweet obsolete or whether the two
sweeteners can coexist since NutraSweet is primarily a
diet-oriented ingredient.
   NutraSweet Co. is under the gun to score a big hit with
Sweetener 2000. The patent on its best-selling artifical
sweetener expires Dec. 14, 1992. After that, competitors will
be free to produce rival versions of aspartame, which
NutraSweet sells under the NutraSweet brand name. The biggest
use for NutraSweet, which holds 75% of the $1 billion
artificial sweetener market world-wide, is in soft drinks. It
also is used in about 3,000 other products.
   NutraSweet officials predict the company's nearly $1
billion in annual sales will decrease about $250 million in
the first year the patent expires. Competitors, now in the
wings, will force the company to lower its prices. Last year,
NutraSweet contributed 20% of parent Monsanto's $909 million
in pretax earnings.
   Already, some of NutraSweet's biggest customers eagerly
await the post-patent era. Over the years NutraSweet has
antagonized many of them because, in holding a classic
monopoly, it not only charged exorbitant prices but also
forced customers to use its distinctive red-and-white swirl
logo on their packaging.
   "If we were able to satisfy ourselves that by not doing
business with NutraSweet, we wouldn't lose any business, we
would make a change, based on our feelings at this point,"
says M. L. Lowenkron, chief executive officer of A&amp;W Brands
Inc., a White Plains, N.Y.-based soft-drink bottler.
   Undeterred, NutraSweet is beginning to inform its
customers of its new super-sweetener and plans to ply them
with samples in a cola formulation.
   The new sweetener is made of two related compounds -- aryl
ureas and trisubstitued guanidines. It was discovered about
two years ago by researchers at the Claude Bernard University
in Lyon, France, who hold its patent. NutraSweet has
exclusive licensing rights.
   But some industry experts question whether Sweetener 2000
might be too much of a good thing. Among other objections,
Mel Wolkstein, a consultant at Reach Associates Inc., warns
that the new sweetener is so concentrated that it "may be
difficult to control in end products."
