<TEXT>
   NutraSweet Co. will announce next week that it has developed a low-calorie, low-cholesterol fat substitute, sources close to the company said. 

   The product, which will be unveiled at a press conference Jan. 27, is derived partially from milk proteins, a source said. 
NutraSweet, a Skokie, Ill.-based unit of Monsanto Co., refused to confirm that it has developed such a product, although it has said in the past it was working on one. 

   A fat substitute would give NutraSweet an important new product to complement its successful low-calorie sweetener, aspartame. 
NutraSweet's U.S. patent on aspartame, its only product, expires in 1992, and the company has been scrambling for new products. 
The fat substitute could also open new markets for the sweetener, a former executive said. 

   And it could throw the company into head-to-head competition with industry giant Procter &amp; Gamble Co., which is seeking regulatory approval for its own fat substitute, called olestra. 

   But NutraSweet's product could still be years away from the market. 
The company hasn't yet asked the Food and Drug Administration to approve its fat substitute. 
"The FDA tends to be extraordinarily careful on any food additive because of the immediate impact on the nation's whole food system," said Jay H. Freedman, an analyst with Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. in New York. 

   Nevertheless, rumors of such an announcement helped push Monsanto's stock higher late last week. 
In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, the St. Louis-based chemical and pharmaceutical giant slipped 37.5 cents a share, to close at $80.25. 

   And the potential market for the fat substitute is unclear. 
Such a product -- there are none now on the market -- could potentially be used in anything from cakes and cooking oils to salad dressing and potato chips, but specific uses hinge on properties that aren't yet known. 
For instance, if the additive breaks down at high temperatures -- as the company's NutraSweet brand sweetener initially did -- it couldn't be used in baked goods. 

   In any case, the product is likely to open new markets for NutraSweet's low-calorie sweetener, said Thomas Churchwell, a former vice president of sales who left the company last year. 
Currently, the sweetener can't be used in products like ice cream, because -- while it replaces the sweetness -- it doesn't replace the bulk and other chemical properties of sugar. 
Fat-based products that could be used to replace those properties also add calories. 

   Procter &amp; Gamble, which has been working on its fat substitute for more than two decades, couldn't be reached for comment yesterday. 
But P&amp;G has said olestra is calorie-and-cholesterol-free, and tastes and behaves like any traditional fat. 
The substance is swallowed with a food, but not absorbed in the bloodstream. 
Some studies suggest it can bind with other fats in a product, and take additional calories and cholesterol out of a person's system. 

   Since olestra apparently passes through the body, some analysts and others have suggested that it may pose fewer health questions than a product like NutraSweet's aspartame sweetener, which is taken into the bloodstream. 
However, the FDA will have to determine that olestra doesn't deplete the body of important vitamins or, because of its lubricating properties, cause diarrhea or other digestive problems. 

   The FDA agreed to review P&amp;G's olestra petition last May, but analysts said yesterday it may be another two years before the product is approved. 
Unilever PLC has also said it is working on a fat substitute. 

   Use of all such products has a psychological element, and Mr. Churchwell said opinion is still divided on how successful they will be. 
"One theory is that (a low-calorie ice cream or baked good) is the dream," he said. 
"The other theory is that part of the reason you eat those things is that it's a little sinful." 

