<HL> NutraSweet's Fat Substitute, Seen Beating P&amp;G to Market, Promises Diet Revolution </HL>
<AUTHOR> Wendy L. Wall (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> MTC </CO>
<IN> FOD </IN>
<TEXT>
   In a move that may help to revolutionize the American diet, NutraSweet Co. says it expects to begin selling a low-calorie, cholesterol-free fat substitute within the next 12 to 18 months. 

   The additive, which is called "Simplesse," will likely hit the market before Procter &amp; Gamble Co.'s highly publicized Olestra, another fat substitute. 

   Although the two products are likely to compete in some food categories, Simplesse -- at least initially -- can be used in many products that Olestra can't and vice versa. 
Thus, the NutraSweet product represents a significant broadening of the way fat substitutes will be used. 

   Simplesse is designed to be used in ice cream, margarine, yogurt, processed cheese, salad dressing and a range of other products. 
It is made through a process that changes the size, shape and texture of milk and egg white proteins, says NutraSweet, a Monsanto Co.-unit based in Skokie, Ill. 

   NutraSweet says that Simplesse doesn't change the taste of food. 
But simply by having no taste, it may in fact, slightly change the way certain foods usually taste. 
"It has the feel of fat, but no taste of fat," says Jeanne Voltz, a cookbook author and former food editor who tasted chocolate ice cream made with Simplesse at a press conference in New York yesterday. 
"There was a taste that was missing and a very slight granular quality." 
Still, she adds, "it was a very good, acceptable product." 

   Simplesse has 1 1/3 calories per gram compared with nine calories for fat. 
Thus, a butter substitute made with the new product would have only eight calories per tablespoon vs. 36 for butter or margarine. 
An ounce of cheese made with Simplesse would have 36 calories compared with 82 for regular cheese. 

   "In a society that's looking for light things -- to have their cake and eat it too -- this sounds like a very attractive idea," says Dr. Irwin Rosenberg, head of the human nutrition center on aging at Tufts University. 
"This could have a very significant impact on the market." 

   The move also represents a marketing coup for NutraSweet, which also developed the low-calorie sweetener aspartame. 
Since Simplesse is made from natural ingredients, it doesn't require regulatory approval; P&amp;G's Olestra, a man-made compound, must be approved by the Food and Drug Administration. 

   The clearest drawback to Simplesse is that it can't be used for frying and baking. 
While Olestra is initially expected to be used in cooking oils and similar products, NutraSweet says heat would cause Simplesse to gel and lose its creaminess. 

   "If you put it on toast, it will spread like butter and melt like butter. 
But don't try to fry an egg in it," says Robert Shapiro, NutraSweet's chairman and chief executive officer. 
"We've taught a protein to fool the mouth. 
That doesn't mean it will fool the frying pan." 

   The only other known drawback is that people who are allergic to milk and egg whites could be allergic to Simplesse. 
The company says it isn't aware of any other health concerns. 
In fact, NutraSweet is expected to play up the product's "all-natural" source in its marketing campaign. 

   Simplesse is made through a patented heating and blending process that shapes proteins into balls so small that the tongue perceives them as fluid rather than individual particles. 
That process creates the smoothness, richness and creaminess normally associated with fat, the company says. 

   NutraSweet officials won't estimate the size of the market for Simplesse. 
However, they say retail sales of products in which Simplesse could be used total about $15 billion. 
The additive is expected to be sold at a premium to fat, one official says. 

   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Monsanto's stock jumped $4.75 a share to $83.50. 

   Simplesse could also transform NutraSweet from an ingredient company into a food company in its own right. 
The company sold its aspartame sweetener under the brand name NutraSweet, a strategy that won it wide acclaim and propelled its sales to more than $700 million in fiscal 1986. 
By adopting a trademark name, NutraSweet is opening the way to a similar strategy with its fat substitute. 

   But Mr. Shapiro says the company may have a tougher sales job with Simplesse than it had with NutraSweet, since consumers had seen sugar-substitutes before. 
As a result, the company is considering bringing out its own line of food products containing Simplesse. 

   "Can we maximize the value of this by selling it as an ingredient -- in which case you risk it being a small brand attached to some other brand -- or should we market a brand ourselves?" asks Nick Rosa, the company's vice president of sales. 
NutraSweet could market products through joint ventures, licensing agreements or by making the products itself, Mr. Rosa says. 

   In any case, Simplesse is likely to open new markets for the company's low-calorie sweetener. 
Until now, aspartame couldn't be used in products like ice cream, because -- while it replaced the sweetness -- it didn't replace the bulk and other chemical properties of sugar. 
Simplesse replaces those properties without adding as many calories as fat. 

</TEXT>
