<HL> FDA Urges NutraSweet Co. to Submit New Fat Substitute for Review by Agency </HL>
<AUTHOR> Wendy L. Wall (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> MTC </CO>
<IN> FOD </IN>
<G> FDA </G>
<TEXT>
   NutraSweet Co.'s widely trumpeted unveiling of its new fat substitute turned sour as the U.S. Food and Drug Administration strongly urged the company to submit the product for review, a development that is almost certain to delay its introduction. 

   At a meeting with NutraSweet officials yesterday afternoon, FDA Commissioner Frank E. Young gave the company three options for the new product, named Simplesse: submit it to the FDA for one of two types of agency reviews -- or put it on the market and risk FDA seizures. 

   The agency's move represents a serious miscalculation by NutraSweet, which unveiled the low-calorie, cholesterol-free fat substitute at a highly publicized news briefing Wednesday. 
At the briefing, the Monsanto Co. unit declared that because Simplesse was made of natural ingredients, it wouldn't require FDA approval. 

   But the introduction apparently caught the FDA off guard. 
The accompanying fanfare helped trigger the agency's action, Mr. Young said. 
"Usually, (developments that don't require FDA approval) aren't trumpeted. 
Here there were press conferences, tastings, a 110-trombone effect," he said. 
"If it's really just a cooking process, then there's no need for all this hoopla." 

   NutraSweet's claim that Simplesse wouldn't require FDA approval was widely seen as a major advantage of the product. 
Among other things, it meant NutraSweet could bring its fat substitute to market much faster than competing brands. 

   NutraSweet has said Simplesse is made from milk and egg-white proteins through a technical process that changes their physical -- but not their chemical -- properties. 
Thus, the company argued that Simplesse would fall under the category of foods "generally recognized as safe," which don't require a complete FDA review. 
Food technologists and food-law attorneys said yesterday that the product sounds like it belongs in that category. 

   Although companies can ask the agency to affirm that new products fall into that category, they generally aren't required to do so. 

   "There's lots of precedent for (the agency) not requiring FDA approval" in such cases, said Merrill Thompson, a Chicago attorney who represents food companies. 
He said problems may have developed because "this was handled in a way that blindsided or embarrassed the agency." 
Added Theodore Labuza, a professor of food science at the University of Minnesota: "This is a legal issue, rather than a toxicological one." 

   NutraSweet officials who attended the meeting couldn't be reached for comment. 
A NutraSweet spokesman said he had no immediate comment on the meeting. 

   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange yesterday, Monsanto closed at $83.625 a share, up 12.5 cents. 

   Mr. Young said he urged the company to either allow the FDA to affirm that the product is "generally recognized as safe," or submit the food additive for a complete FDA review. 
Although NutraSweet could legally bring Simplesse to market without prior FDA approval, the agency could seize the product if it is concerned that it is unsafe, the commissioner said. 

   All three options pose serious problems for the company. 
One option, filing a GRAS petition, would likely be quickest -- taking anywhere from a few months to several years -- but would probably force the company to divulge trade secrets. 

   A complete review, a second option, could drag on for years. 
In fact, some experts speculated that the company shunned the FDA review process partly because of the 10-year battle it waged to get its aspartame sweetener approved. 

   NutraSweet could try to wage a public-relations battle, counting on the attention Simplesse has received to pressure the FDA into a quick approval of the product. 
"NutraSweet has been in the thick of it," says Mr. Labuza, referring to the company's protracted aspartame battle. 

</TEXT>
