FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnson &amp; Johnson said the Food and Drug Administration accepted for formal review its new artificial sweetener, sucralose. 

   The sweetener could eventually compete with Monsanto Co.'s highly successful aspartame, which is marketed as NutraSweet. 
An FDA spokesman said the agency's reviews of new food additives can take as long as several years. 
He declined to comment specifically on the sucralose review. 

   Johnson &amp; Johnson, a health-care products concern, said sucralose, which is based on a derivative of sugar, is "600 times sweeter" than sugar but has no calories and doesn't promote tooth decay. 
The sweetener is being jointly developed by Johnson &amp; Johnson and Tate &amp; Lyle PLC, a London-based sugar refiner. 

   Johnson &amp; Johnson said the product has undergone eight years of safety tests in the U.S. and Britain, using laboratory animals and human subjects. 
Those tests indicated that sucralose "is safe for human consumption," Johnson &amp; Johnson said. 

   Tests also indicated that sucralose is stable "even when stored over long periods or at elevated temperatures," the company said. 
That property could make it popular for use in food processing, a spokesman said. 

   Johnson &amp; Johnson said it plans to market the product through its McNeil Specialty Products unit. 

   A spokesman for St. Louis-based Monsanto's NutraSweet Co. unit said, "We've always known there would be competition, but we don't know that much about (Johnson &amp; Johnson's) product, and it's too early to tell" what effect, if any, it will have on Monsanto, a chemical, electronics and drug concern. 

   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Johnson &amp; Johnson shares closed at $90.50, up 25 cents. 

