<HL> NutraSweet Seems
Clear of Complaints
It Causes Headaches
---
Human Trial Finds Sweetener
Isn't Any More Likely
A Culprit Than Placebo
---
By Jerry E. Bishop</HL>
<DD> 11/06/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> MTC
FOOD &amp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Scientists relieved another headache afflicting NutraSweet low-calorie artificial sweetener. 

   A human experiment at Duke University found that NutraSweet, the Monsanto Co. brand name for aspartame sweetener, wasn't any more likely to cause headaches in people than a placebo. 

   The experiment was undertaken after the federal Centers for Disease Control reported it had received several hundred complaints of headaches among NutraSweet users following the sweetener's marketing in 1981. 

   The Duke experiment involved 40 volunteers who had complained to the manufacturer that they suffered headaches after consuming NutraSweet. 
The volunteers were hospitalized at the university's medical center in Durham, N.C., where their diets, health and blood chemistry could be monitored. 

   On the third day, each volunteer took a capsule three times during the day. 
Some received capsules containing an inert placebo, while others received identical capsules containing high doses of NutraSweet. 
A similar "challenge" was conducted on the fifth day, except that those who previously had received placebos were given capsules of NutraSweet and those who had earlier taken NutraSweet received placebos. 
Neither the volunteers nor the dispensers knew at the time which capsules were which. 

   Of the 40 volunteers, 26 complained of mild to moderate headaches after taking the capsules. 
Eight of these developed headaches only after taking NutraSweet but 12 developed headaches only after taking placebo capsules. 
The remaining six developed headaches after taking both kinds of capsules. 

   The experiment, reported in this week's New England Journal of Medicine, was funded by the federal National Institutes of Health and NutraSweet Co., a subsidiary of Monsanto, a St. Louis-based chemical and pharmaceutical concern. 

   Several controversies have surrounded NutraSweet since its marketing was begun, including the possibility of neurological problems in certain people, and whether it increases the appetites of obese people. 

</TEXT>
