<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The unprecedented truth-in-labeling changes
announced last month by the government will trigger much more
than a massive relabeling of food products. One of the
foremost -- but unheralded -- objectives of the changes is to
spur the food industry into developing more healthful
products.
   And by all accounts, the industry is prepared to do just
that. The first of thousands of new edibles -- lower in fat,
sodium and other undesirable nutrients than ever before --
will show up on supermarket shelves by 1993 as food
manufacturers adapt to a new era of mandatory nutrition
labeling and strict rules for making health claims.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Until now, marketers have been relatively free to tinker
with words on the food label -- without altering what's in
the package," says Food and Drug Administration Commissioner
David Kessler. He and other regulators are counting on the
new labeling regulations to help shift the industry's
creative efforts from the marketing executive's "word
processor to the laboratory," as Dr. Kessler puts it.
   The joint FDA-Agriculture Department labeling initiative
will require "a tremendous reformulation" by the May 1993
compliance deadline, says Eric Larson, packaged-foods analyst
for First Boston Corp. in Chicago. "For the first year, you
will see a lot of companies trying to make their products
comply. Product innovation will come in a second wave." He
expects many of the new foods to be concocted with
proprietary ingredients, including fat substitutes and
artificial sweeteners, many of which are awaiting FDA
clearance.
   The consensus is that cutting fat will be the primary
research-and-development focus. "We are going to see attempts
to get the fat content down, and then see attempts to develop
better products with no fat," says Alan Hugunin, director of
product development at the National Food Processors
Association laboratory in Dublin, Calif. The new federal
rules also will remove various disincentives for developing
and marketing healthier versions of so-called standardized
foods.
   The $280 billion food industry has been in regulatory
limbo for months, waiting for FDA and Agriculture Department
officials to decide on scores of labeling rules that, though
seemingly picayune, will have vast potential to help -- or
hurt -- corporate bottom lines. Many companies have been
holding off on new-product research and development, pending
the issuance of final rules next November.
   But a new survey by Prepared Foods, a trade publication,
portends an industrywide rise in the development of more
healthful products. Of 421 food companies polled, 71% said
they plan to pour more dollars into new reduced-fat and
reduced-calorie products as well as diet foods for weight
watchers, according to the survey, which will be published
next month.
   Daniel Best, technical director of the Chicago-based
publication, says he expects the wave of new products to come
after companies have relabeled and reformulated existing
products. Meantime, manufacturers of ingredients such as salt
enhancers and fat replacers, including novel starches and soy
proteins, are complaining about slow sales due to regulatory
uncertainties.
   "There's tremendous demand for them building," says Mr.
Best. "I think you will see an upsurge of ingredient sales
once the companies know what the regulations are." Such
sales, he adds, will serve as the "leading indicator" of
innovation-and new-product launches.
   The marketplace has seen a steady rise in new products
bearing health-related marketing claims such as "lite" and
"no cholesterol." Last year, 10,301 new items were
introduced, up from 9,192 in 1989 and 8,183 in 1988,
according to Gorman's New Product News. Many of the claims,
however, have proved to be misleading, irrelevant or
fictitious, prompting enforcement actions by the FDA and
attorneys general from several states.
   Management at Kraft General Foods Inc., the nation's
largest food company, believes the new federal labeling
regulations will "encourage both good communication and
product innovation." Says Michael Mudd, spokesman for the
Philip Morris Cos. unit: "If companies want to use {health}
claims, they are going have to develop products that merit
them."
   But the anticipated cornucopia of more healthful food
choices isn't likely to meet expectations unless the FDA
speeds the approval of new food additives and ingredients.
   The agency has 400 petitions under review, including scads
of artificial sweeteners, some of which have been pending for
five to 10 years. Monsanto Co.'s NutraSweet Co. unit, for
example, wants to use its aspartame product in everything
from breakfast cereals to hard candy, while Stroh Brewery Co.
wants to sweeten malt beverages with aspartame. Hoechst AG's
Hoechst Celanese Corp. unit is seeking FDA clearance to use
its sweetener Sunette in beverages and baked goods.
   Several fat substitutes are also under FDA review as
companies vie for position in the battle for the dieter's
palate. Procter &amp; Gamble Co. has been waiting since 1987 for
the go-ahead to market Olestra, a synthetic concoction of
fatty acids and sugar that has the taste and texture of fat
but no calories. The backlog includes a Kraft General Foods
fat substitute, made from milk and egg-white protein.
   "We need a better response time," says Mr. Hugunin. "The
FDA has to be very cautious about what it approves, but it
seems like it drags out forever."
   The FDA blames the backlog on complex petitions and the
need to ask companies for additional food-safety data. "None
of us are happy with the time it takes," says Alan Rulis, the
agency's director of food and color additives. A management
consultant is being hired to study how the review process can
be streamlined without compromising public health.
   The agency, meanwhile, is moving to eliminate another
major obstacle to innovation. By next November, the industry
will no longer be fettered by archaic "standards of identity"
that hamper the marketing of lower-fat products. Currently,
cheddar cheese, for example, must be called something other
than cheese if it contains less than 50% fat. And butter
isn't butter unless it's at least 80% fat.
   "Who wants to make a big investment {in product
development} just to call something `artificial' or
`imitation'?" asks Sherwin Gardner, senior vice president,
science and technology, for the Grocery Manufacturers of
America.
   As part of the nutrition-labeling initiative, the FDA
intends to spare manufacturers from having to petition for
changes in a standard or having to obtain a series of
temporary exemptions in order to market a low-fat
standardized food.
   "This is a breakthrough," says Allen Rosenfeld, spokesman
for Public Voice for Food and Health Policy, a consumer
group. "It removes a huge disincentive to innovation."
</TEXT>
