<HEAD>FDA Says Banned Artificial Sweetener May Make Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The artificial sweetener cyclamate may find
its way back on the market after being banned for 20 years as a
suspected carcinogen, but probably not before next year, the Food
and Drug Administration says.
   The FDA said Tuesday it is continuing a review of the sweetener,
commenting in response to a Washington Post story that quoted an
FDA official as saying the agency ``made a mistake'' in banning
cyclamate.
   The agency has been considering lifting the cyclamate ban since
1982, and though studies have challenged initial claims that the
sweetener causes bladder cancer, other safety concerns remain.
   ``The final studies aren't expected until summer and fall, and
then the FDA would have to review that data and there would have to
be some time for public comment, so it may be hard to get all that
completed this year, and that's assuming the studies are
favorable,'' said FDA spokesman Bill Grigg.
   Among the concerns are cyclamate's effects on blood pressure and
whether it causes genetic damage, testicular atrophy or promotes
tumor growth.
   The Post quoted Robert Scheuplein, acting director of the office
of toxicological services for the FDA's Center for Food Safety and
Applied Nutrition, as saying: ``I have no reluctance in saying that
with cyclamate we made a mistake.''
   Calls seeking comment from Scheuplein were referred to the FDA's
press office, and spokesman Emil Corwin said no interviews would be
granted.
   Grigg declined to comment directly on Scheuplein's remark, but
noted the FDA ``said as far back as 1973 that if the larger (base
of) data showed that the early data on which we based the decision
(to ban cyclamate) were faulty, that we would reverse it.''
   Scheuplein's comment was encouraging to the Calorie Control
Council, an industry group representing soft drink and dietetic
food manufacturers that has been seeking to reintroduce cyclamate.
   ``We look forward to reapproval as soon as possible,'' said
council spokesman Keith Keeney.
   The council and Abbott Laboratories of North Chicago, Ill., the
major producer of cyclamate, in 1982 filed the latest of many
petitions to the FDA for reconsideration of the ban.
   Cyclamate was first used in foods and beverages in the early
1950s, before enactment of a law later that decade requiring
pre-market review of food additives. It was banned in 1969, and the
FDA reaffirmed that ban in 1976 and 1980.
   The FDA's Cancer Assessment Committee concluded in 1985 that
cyclamate does not by itself cause cancer. In a report later that
year, the National Academy of Sciences said cyclamate does not
cause cancer but may play a secondary role that should be examined
more closely.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest took issue with
the findings of the reports. Spokeswoman Lisa Lefferts said ``I'm
not sure the jury's in on cancer,'' and the center has further
concerns about the possibility that cyclamate causes testicular
atrophy, inhibits growth and damages chromosomes.
   ``We don't think FDA is likely to reverse its decision on
cyclamate. If they do they're going to have to make a lot of
evidence disappear,'' Lefferts said.
   The most common non-sugar sweeteners used in the United States
are aspartame, or Nutrasweet, and saccharin. The FDA proposed to
ban saccharin in 1977 because it is suspected of causing cancer,
but Congress has allowed it to continue on the market with a
cancer-related warning label.
   The FDA last year approved acesulfame potassium, or Sunette, as
a calorie-free sweetener for table use, and for chewing gum, dry
beverage mixes, instant coffee and tea, gelatins, puddings and
non-dairy creamers.
</TEXT>
