<HEAD>FDA Approves New Artificial Sweetener</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is allowing
use of a no-calorie sweetener as a table sugar substitute and
ingredient in some food products.
   The substance, acesulfame potassium, was developed in West
Germany and is used in 20 other countries as an additive in various
pharmaceutical products, some baked goods and candies, the Food and
Drug Administration said Wednesday.
   Regulations permitting use of the sweetener, to be marketed in
the United States as ``Sunette,'' take effect upon publication in
the Federal Register today.
   The FDA is allowing its use in chewing gum, dry beverage mixes,
instant coffee, instant tea, gelatins, puddings and non-dairy
creamers.
   However, the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a
consumer interest group, told the FDA it was concerned that the
sweetener may have caused tumors found in laboratory animals.
   But the FDA said the tumors were ``what could routinely be
expected'' and not due to feeding with Sunette.
   Sunette is a product of the Hoechst Celanese Corp. of
Somerville, N.J., a subsidiary of Hoechst AG of Frankfurt, West
Germany. The company did not seek FDA approval to use Sunette in
soft drinks.
   The FDA deferred action on the company's request to use the
sweetener in candies and other confections in the United States.
   In the past the agency has interpreted the Food, Drug and
Cosmetic Act as barring the use of non-nutritive sweeteners in
candies.
   Sunette is said to be 200 times sweeter than sugar. It joins
saccharin, another no-calorie sweetener, and the low-calorie sugar
substitute aspartame on the U.S. market.
</TEXT>
