<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending, the driving force behind
eight years of U.S. economic expansion, did not budge in October,
the government said in a report analysts contend was further
evidence of a recession.
   Accounting for two-thirds of the nation's economic activity,
consumer spending was unchanged from September at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $3.73 trillion, the Commerce Department
said Thursday.
   ``The consumer has retrenched,'' said economist Gilbert Benz of
the Swiss Bank Corp. in New York. ``It clearly supports those who
say we're in a recession.''
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has charged 12 people with
attempting to distribute more than $500 million in securities
stolen from companies in New York and London.
   Those charged were accused of taking part in a conspiracy to
distribute about 291 million British pounds (about $550 million) in
treasury bills and certificates of deposit issued by the Bank of
England. The bank's employees had been robbed of the money at knife
point on May 2, according to the indictment, which was returned by
a federal grand jury in Manhattan and unsealed Thursday.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. stock climbed for the third consecutive
day after a published report said the company was considering a
stock buyback.
   The company said it had no comment on Thursday's report, but its
stock jumped $4.87{ a share to $165.75 in trading on the New York
Stock Exchange. That followed a $5.87{ a share advance on Wednesday
and a $2.25 rise on Tuesday. The media company's stock remains well
below its high for the year of $206 a share, however.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community has imposed
penalties known as anti-dumping duties on U.S. and Japanese imports
of aspartame, an artificial sweetener used in soft drinks and food.
   The EC Commission on Thursday said NutraSweet, the U.S.
exporter, charged less than half in Europe for its product than in
the United States causing ``material injury'' to Holland Sweetener
Co, the EC's only aspartame maker.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A biotechnology watchdog has charged in a
lawsuit that the National Dairy Board is illegally promoting a
growth hormone being used experimentally in cows to increase milk
production.
   Jeremy Rifkin, president of the Washington-based Foundation on
Economic Trends, has used a variety of legal maneuvers to try to
block the use of bovine growth hormone on the grounds that it is
unsafe for human health.
   Thursday's action is based on documents he obtained under the
Freedom of Information Act.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VEVEY, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's biggest food company,
Nestle SA, and the largest soft drink concern, The Coca-Cola Co.,
have signed a deal to set up a joint venture in beverages, the
companies said.
   The statement on Thursday said the two multinationals would be
equal partners in the new company which would manufacture and
market bases and concentrates for the production of ready-to-drink
coffee and tea drinks.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community Commission has
proposed developing a green-labeling system for consumer goods that
would denote products that are environmentally sound.
   EC Environment Commissioner Carlo Ripa de Meana said Thursday's
proposal would put industries under pressure to make ecologically
sound products. He said a panel of scientists and other experts
from the 12 EC states would identify which products could sport the
label showing a daisy encircled by 12 stars.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aerospace giant
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm GmbH plans to cut 10 percent of its
workforce at its main German production complex at Ottobrunn, the
IG Metall labor union said.
   The company, also known as MBB, is the aerospace subsidiary of
Germany's largest industrial group, Daimler-Benz AG. At Ottobrunn,
MBB's main production complex, the union said on Thursday the
company plans to trim 700 jobs in the aircraft construction sector
and another 300 jobs in the defense technology section during 1991.
   ---
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial News Network Inc., which operates a
business channel on cable television but is embroiled in a
financial controversy of its own, says it expects to report a $72.5
million loss for fiscal 1990.
   The company, whose biggest shareholer is the owner of the
United Press International wire service, also said on Thursday it
expects to report a loss of $25 million for the first quarter of
its current fiscal year.
   ---
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lost ground Thursday in a seesaw session
punctuated by rumors and technical selling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 16.34 points to
close at 2,518.81.
   Bonds fell. The dollar bounded higher as gold prices gained.
   Oil prices slipped in volatile trading.
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed sharply higher.
</TEXT>
