<LP>
   Diet colas are losing their sales fizz, and beverage
makers are scrambling to find a replacement.
   It's a matter of considerable urgency: Diet drinks fueled
the soft-drink industry's rapid growth in the 1980s. Now, to
drum up sales in a slowing market, the industry is looking at
such products as canned coffees, "new age" sodas, sports
drinks and juice drinks. Yesterday, for instance, Pepsi-Cola
said it would begin to distribute Ocean Spray juices in
January.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Companies may also reformulate diet colas with new types
of sweeteners and aim them at new audiences.
   Whatever the ultimate answer, the fact is that beverage
makers are confronting a dramatically slowing market. For
much of the 1980s, the industry grew between 4% and 5%
annually -- primarily because of the exploding popularity of
diet colas. Today, industry growth has shrunk to between 2%
and 3%. Most notably, sales of diet soft drinks, which now
constitute 30% of the market, are no longer growing at
double-digit rates. This year, in a maturing market, sales of
both diet Coke and Diet Pepsi are expected to increase just
3% to 4% overall.
   Niche products like iced coffees or mountain blackberry
soda (made by Clearly Canadian Beverage Corp. in Vancouver)
may help soft-drink sales, but beverage executives doubt such
products represent the next blockbuster needed to carry the
industry through the 1990s. Specialty drinks "are never going
to be what the cola segment will be," observes J. Bruce
Llewellyn, chairman and chief executive officer of
Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co. "No matter what
hocus-pocus there is, it doesn't amount to a hill of beans
compared with Coca-Cola."
   Or compared with its low-calorie cousin. Diet Coke, said
Roberto C. Goizueta, head of Coca-Cola Co., at its
introduction in 1982, "may well be the most successful new
product in the history of the soft-drink industry." He was
close. By 1984, diet Coke was the third most popular soft
drink in the country. In the same year, Coke and others began
substituting NutraSweet for saccharine in their diet drinks,
markedly improving the taste. More recently, beverage makers
have also begun chasing after men (women had been the first
target) by advertising diet drinks during sporting events.
   The upshot: Increases in sales of 20% for much of the
decade, recalls Ron Wilson, president of Philadelphia
Coca-Cola Bottling. "It was a gift horse to us."
   But the party is over. One reason is that low calories
aren't enough for many consumers these days. They also want
something that's healthy -- or appears to be.
   Enter "new age" sodas: fruity, clear beverages, often sold
in glass bottles, that have a wholesome air about them.
Clearly Canadian Beverage, with flavors like orchard peach,
sold in chunky blue glass bottles, expects sales this year of
$200 million, up from $17.3 million just two years ago.
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola is considering packaging Fresca, its
diet grapefruit drink, in a green glass bottle next year.
PepsiCo Inc., based in Purchase, N.Y., says it wants to get
into the segment in a big way but has yet to see sales take
off in test markets for H2Oh, the flavored bottled water it
has been testing for two years. "We're not going to sit by
the sidelines and watch the thing called `new age' grow
without participating," promises David Novak, PepsiCo's vice
president for marketing.
   For now Pepsi is getting into the fastgrowing juice
segment. Yesterday, the company said it plans to distribute
Ocean Spray single-serve drinks in stores and vending
machines nationwide by the end of 1992. The deal will enable
Pepsi to profit from the 10% annual growth in the $12 billion
fruit-drink and juice market, says Michael Bellas, president
of Beverage Marketing Corp.
   In another area, Coke and Pepsi are testing sports drinks
to vie with Gatorade, the Quaker Oats Co. product that
controls 88% of the $1 billion retail market for sports
drinks. Pepsi, which originally tested a Mountain Dew sports
drink last year, switched the name to "All Sport" and came
out with three new flavors in May. The company expects to
roll out cans and bottles nationally in the second quarter of
next year. Coke has its sports drink, PowerAde, in 1,000
outlets, or only about 0.3% of its fountain accounts.
   But the new product expected to make the biggest splash is
iced and canned coffee, and -- to a lesser extent -- brewed
and flavored teas. This is despite the fact that U.S.
consumption of coffee has been flat for a decade and sales of
tea have fallen steadily. Beverage executives maintain that
canned coffee is convenient and that consumers increasingly
prefer cold and sweet drinks to hot ones.
   Coke and Nestle expect their Mocha Cooler and Ice Breaker,
flavored coffees now in test market, to be rolled out in cans
and fountains next spring. Beverage industry experts expect
Pepsi to team up with Thomas J. Lipton Inc. to distribute a
new line of their own brewed tea and coffee. Kraft General
Foods, a unit of Philip Morris Cos., has been testing Cappio,
an iced-cappuccino drink, in Arizona since August 1990.
   Still, whether they be coffees, power drinks or "new age"
sodas, niche markets have drawbacks. To begin with, products
-- and product loyalty -- appear transient at best. In the
mid-1980s, Original New York Seltzer Co. enjoyed phenomenal
growth, capturing half a share point in the $46 billion
domestic soft-drink market. But the company's products, a
victim of fickle tastes, have retreated as of late.
   Then there are the beverage companies' giant distribution
systems -- geared toward cranking out soft drinks on a
massive scale and unable to benefit handsomely from niche
products. Such markets account for only $1.5 billion in
sales, according to Beverage Marketing Corp.'s Mr. Bellas,
while diet colas alone bring in $11 billion.
   All of which means that soft-drink companies will also
attempt to rejuvenate their diet drinks. Pepsi is planning a
"major all-out assault" to promote diet cola next year, in
stores and through national media, according to Mr. Novak,
the vice president for marketing.
   Both Coke and Pepsi are expected to set their advertising
to appeal to as broad an audience as possible. While men now
account for 43% of sales of diet colas, according to Simmons
Market Research, women still represent the greatest
opportunity for increased sales. "We don't want to take them
for granted," says Mr. Wilson at Philadelphia Coca-Cola
Bottling. To refocus on women, for example, Coke may scale
back use of endorsers like football players.
   Older drinkers -- the over-45 set, whose tastes seem to
favor less-sweet products and whose life styles become more
sedentary -- will also be a target of new marketing efforts,
as will blacks and Hispanics. Today, according to Simmons
Market Research, minority groups consume 20% less diet soda
than whites. To reach those groups, soft-drink makers will
"have to show them that you don't drink diet colas to look
like skinny white women," says Tom Pirko, president of
Bevmark Inc., a consulting firm.
   One way to do that, suggests Mr. Pirko, may be to to make
an appeal based on taste -- particularly if beverage makers
adopt new sweeteners in their diet drinks. That may occur as
early as December 1992, when the patent on the artificial
sweetener aspartame, held by NutraSweet, expires. "It will
kick a bunch of life into the diet category," predicts Mr.
Pirko.
   Perhaps, but "The company that guesses wrong on
replacement sweeteners could make the brouhaha {in 1985} over
`new Coke' look like a minor story," says Jesse Myers,
publisher of the trade publication Beverage Digest. "It could
be a marketing bonanza or a marketing fiasco."
