<LP>
   DEERFIELD, Ill. -- Monsanto Co.'s NutraSweet Co. unit said
it would dismiss as much as 12% of its work force, or between
170 and 200 employees, in a reorganization that combines its
two key food ingredients businesses.
   The company said its NutraSweet artificial sweetener and
Simplesse fat substitute products would be marketed to the
food and beverage industries in tandem. Previously each
product called on the industries separately.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a result, jobs are likely to be eliminated from the
company's research and development, business ventures and
corporate staffs as well as at the four plants that make
NutraSweet. Businesses exempt from cuts include Simplesse,
Simple Pleasures, a frozen dairy dessert, and Equal, a sugar
substitute.
   Although a NutraSweet spokesman said the reorganization
didn't indicate any unhappiness by Monsanto, industry sources
say the company is anxious to improve the return on its
costly investment in Simplesse, which has been on the market
about a year.
   A Monsanto spokeswoman said the costs associated with the
work force reduction would not result in a charge against
future earnings. The dismissals are to begin shortly.
   Separately, NutraSweet's Simplesse Co. unit said that
Simple Pleasures is expanding its dessert line with several
flavors, and would be moving into the New York, Philadelphia
and Boston markets after achieving what it said was a 19%
market share elsewhere in the super-premium ice cream
category.
   Simplesse also said it was awaiting Food and Drug
Administration approval for use of the fat substitute in
mayonnaise, cheese, sour cream, dips, salad dressing, yogurt
and cheesecake.
</TEXT>
