<HL> Monsanto Says Sales
Will Rise in '87, Cites
Chemicals, Herbicide</HL>
<DD> 02/19/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> MTC
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM) </IN>
<DATELINE> ST. LOUIS  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsanto Co. expects sales to be up moderately this year, largely because of strong chemical sales and continuing improvement in sales of its Roundup herbicide, Richard J. Mahoney, chairman and chief executive officer, said. 

   But Mr. Mahoney wouldn't speculate about Monsanto's earnings for either the 1987 first quarter or full year. 
He also declined to comment on analysts' projections that the company will earn between $5.40 and $6.25 a share in 1987. 

   In 1986, Monsanto had net income of $433 million, or $5.55 a share, on sales of $6.88 billion. 

   Sales of Lasso, one of the company's two major herbicides, aren't likely to rise enough to offset the effect of recent price cuts, Mr. Mahoney said in an interview. 
Last month, Monsanto said it was cutting the price of Lasso about 6%, the first such cut for the herbicide, to counter price cutting by competitors. 

   Mr. Mahoney said he expects Monsanto's Fischer Controls International Inc. unit to return to "strong" profitability this year, after posting an operating loss of $66 million in 1986. 
The unit, which makes valves and automated-process-control gear, has been hurt by sluggish economic growth and a depressed oil-processing industry. 

   Users of Monsanto's NutraSweet artificial sweetener are likely to continue to make inventory adjustments in the first quarter, trimming sales, Mr. Mahoney said. 
NutraSweet sales fell sharply in the 1986 fourth quarter as makers of powdered soft drinks reduced their inventories. 
However, Mr. Mahoney said fundamental demand for NutraSweet continues to rise, because diet soft drinks still are raising their share of the overall soft-drink market. 

   Sales of Monsanto's Roundup herbicide rose 25% by volume in 1986, more than overcoming the effect of some price reductions, Mr. Mahoney said. 
New Roundup mixtures aimed at the home garden and industrial markets sold well, he said. 

   Mr. Mahoney said he expects the performance of Monsanto's chemical business, its largest unit, to remain strong. 
However, any recovery of the company's electronics business, which makes silicon wafers, depends on "the elusive semiconductor recovery," he added. 

   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange yesterday, Monsanto shares closed at $79.375, up 50 cents. 

</TEXT>
