<LP>
   Miller Lite, which yanked its $110 million account from
Backer Spielvogel Bates just two months ago, already is on
the air trying to lure younger drinkers with new spots from
ad agency Leo Burnett.
   The new commercials -- one stars "Saturday Night Live"
comic Kevin Nealon in his smarmy "Mr. Subliminal" adman role
-- waste no time in all but killing off Lite's campaign
featuring legions of retired jocks. Curiously, though, they
don't do away with the long-running "tastes great, less
filling" debate created by Backer, a unit of Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi Co. Instead, the new spots answer the debate. Sort
of.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Is Miller Lite America's favorite because it's less
filling or because it tastes great?" the ads ask. The answer:
"Yes."
   The ads are the first work from Chicago-based Leo Burnett,
which won the Philip Morris beer brand in March in the
biggest account switch the ad industry has seen in years.
Burnett inherited a huge brand that nevertheless faces big
problems. After 17 years of ads chock-full of retired jocks
-- spots that all began to look the same -- Lite is losing
share to such competitors as Bud Light and Coors Light. At
the same time, Lite's drinkers are older than those of its
competitors.
   "They have to aim at a younger audience," says Jerry
Steinman, publisher of Beer Marketer's Insight, a West Nyack,
N.Y., trade publication. According to Beverage Marketing
Corp., a New York consultant, 23% of Lite drinkers are older
than age 50, far more than for other light beers. Only 47% of
Lite drinkers are in the desirable 18-to-34-year-old age
group, for example, compared with 57% for Michelob Light's
drinkers.
   The new Lite commercials clearly aim to remedy that
problem. As "Mr. Subliminal," Saturday Night Live's Mr.
Nealon wends his way through a crowded bar that looks like
the setting for one of Coors Light's rock 'n' roll
pickup-spot ads. "What they won't do in commercials these
days," he says, adding under his breath, "buy Miller Lite."
He makes his way to the bar, where he uses "subliminal"
seduction to hit on a svelte young babe: "Hi (your place).
Would you like to join me for a Lite (your treat) -- it's on
me." "Okay," she answers, "but it's my treat."
   A second commercial centers yet again on a yuppie putting
the moves on a woman at a bar. This time, every question he
asks her, she answers "yes" -- ranging from "Do you wear
Spandex all the time, or is it a Tuesday thing?" to "Is
Miller Lite America's favorite because it's less filling or
because it tastes great?"
   Yet Miller is clearly skittish about moving away too
abruptly from its retired-jock campaign, which did, after
all, help make Lite the best-selling light beer in the
country. While the company began airing its new commercials
last weekend, it did so without fanfare and played down the
new ads when questioned. "It's a continuation of the
advertising which talks about tastes-great and less-filling
attributes," a spokesman said.
   Indeed, one new commercial even uses jocks, though they
aren't retired and they aren't arguing about tasting great or
being less filling. But the spot, which aired last weekend,
won't be seen again. One of its stars is Don Zimmer, who was
released yesterday as manager of the Chicago Cubs. In the
commercial, he and Cincinnati Reds manager Lou Piniella
argued over Astroturf, with Mr. Piniella, an Astroturf fan,
comparing it to "America's favorite light beer. . . . It
leaves out all the things you don't need -- tricky hops, slow
infielders, ugly grass stains." The spot had aired only in
Chicago and Cincinnati anyway, the spokesman said.
   Miller faces an enormous challenge in trying to attract
new drinkers while keeping its core group of loyalists. For
example, given its ingrained macho advertising, it would be
difficult to launch a campaign geared toward women, as
Michelob Light is currently doing in women's magazines. That
ad pictures torn-out headline snippets like "Lose fat while
you shop" and "Blast jiggly hips and thighs," and advises,
"Relax. You're OK. Improve your beer."
   "There is no way to renovate Miller Lite. You can't take
something that is so deeply ingrained into the American
consciousness -- the images of aging jocks -- and effectively
change it into another breed," contends Tom Pirko, president
of Bevmark Inc., a Los Angeles-based consulting company. He
believes Miller's only hope of tackling light-beer
competitors is to tout an entirely different brand, like its
new Light Ultra beer. It should tinker with Lite's
advertising, he says, but "you can't take a cow and change it
into a horse."
                                                                                                       

   Robbins Named Lintas CEO
                                                                                                       

   Kenneth L. Robbins was named chairman and chief executive
officer of Lintas: Worldwide, succeeding William Weithas, who
moves to the new post of vice chairman of Interpublic Group,
Lintas's parent.
   Mr. Robbins, 55 years old, was seen as the likely
successor to Mr. Weithas. Mr. Robbins had headed Lintas's
London-based international operations for the past five years
and previously was head of Lintas's flagship New York office.
   Mr. Weithas, 62, has been chairman of the agency since
1979, when it was acquired by Interpublic Group. He oversaw
the integration of Lintas into the holding company. In his
new post, Mr. Weithas said he will be "keeping a dialogue
with major clients," giving Interpublic Chairman Philip Geier
more time for other duties.
   Separately, Interpublic Group's board voted to increase
its quarterly dividend to 21 cents a share from 19 cents. The
dividend will be payable June 17 to stock of record May 31.
                                                                                                       

   NutraSweet's New Campaign
                                                                                                       

   NutraSweet Co. next week begins a new ad campaign, playing
up its artificial sweetener's 10th anniversary and seeking to
cement consumer loyalty.
   The effort comes as NutraSweet, a unit of Monsanto, braces
for the expiration of its patent on the aspartame sweetener
late next year -- and for a flood of competitors to enter the
category. In anticipation of an end to its monopoly, the
company earlier this year realigned operations to focus more
on its customer base.
   The campaign is the first from Chiat/Day/Mojo, the Venice,
Calif., agency that won the U.S. account last December. Ads
hark back to the sweetener's introduction; a gumball, one of
the first products sweetened with NutraSweet, figures
prominently. The tagline: "Making the world a better place to
eat."
   In one TV spot, the voice-over says nothing but "blah blah
blah" for the entire commercial. Meanwhile, type on the
screen says, "Some studies show that people don't listen to
the words in commercials," and goes on to plug the sweetener.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   CONSOLIDATION: Bausch &amp; Lomb consolidated all
international marketing for its Ray-Ban sunglasses with Young
&amp; Rubicam, New York. Billings couldn't be determined. The
account had been split among a number of different agencies.
Levine, Huntley, Vick &amp; Beaver continues to handle the line
in the U.S.
                                                                                                       

   PRAVDA: Entertainment &amp; Communications Holdings
Organization, Los Angeles, said it signed an advertising
accord with the Soviet daily newspaper Pravda. ECHO, a media
consultancy, will manage all ad sales and marketing for the
paper in the U.S. and Canada. Pravda began to run some
advertising in November.
                                                                                                       

   ACQUISITION: Ogilvy &amp; Mather, a unit of WPP Group,
acquired the 40% of its Hungarian unit it didn't already own.
Budapest agency Mahir, a partner in the venture, is selling
the stake because of potential client conflicts.
                                                                                                       

   PROMOTION: Campbell-Mithun-Esty Advertising, in a showy
display of agency loyalty, is offering an extra week's
vacation to employees who buy or lease a new Jeep or Eagle
vehicle. Campbell-Mithun, a unit of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co.,
has handled the account for Jeep, now a unit of Chrysler,
since 1960.
